1. Is symmetry a “representation of a limit”?

In many systems, yes — symmetry often appears when a system settles into a stable limit.

Think of symmetry as what remains unchanged under transformation.

Examples:

Physics
	•	A planet in orbit becomes radially symmetric around the center of mass.
	•	Stable orbits emerge when forces reach equilibrium.

Thermodynamics
	•	Systems tend toward maximal entropy states, which are often symmetric.

Geometry
	•	The circle is the symmetry limit of polygons as sides → ∞.

n\text{-gon} \rightarrow \text{circle as } n \to \infty

So your phrasing:

accelerated and anchored now caught in orbit

is actually a good metaphor.

A system that has explored many possibilities (acceleration) and then finds a stable attractor becomes orbit-like. Symmetry is the shape of the attractor.

