2. What are radians?

Radians are one of the most important units in mathematics and physics.

A radian measures angles based on arc length relative to radius.

Definition:

\theta = \frac{\text{arc length}}{\text{radius}}

So:

arc length	radius	angle
1	1	1 rad

A full circle has circumference:

2\pi r

Divide by r:

\frac{2\pi r}{r} = 2\pi

So a full circle is:

2\pi \text{ radians}

⸻

Why radians are powerful

Radians remove arbitrary scaling constants.

Example:

Derivative of sine.

Using radians:

\frac{d}{dx}\sin(x) = \cos(x)

Using degrees:

\frac{d}{dx}\sin(x) = \frac{\pi}{180}\cos(x)

Radians make the math cleaner and natural to the geometry.

This is why physics, engineering, and signal processing use them.

